--- machine\system\registry
canonical: Machine\System\Registry

LCS reads its own operational limits — the tunables under this key — by
watching its own configuration subtree. Compiled-in defaults are used at
boot and are always sufficient for correct operation; LCS never enters a
"waiting for configuration" state. Once the first source registers, LCS
reads the values here, validates them, applies the valid ones, and arms
an internal subtree watch so later changes are picked up for the lifetime
of the system. Every parameter is a REG_DWORD.

**Validation is reject-or-keep, never clamp.** A valid value is
hot-swapped into the in-memory configuration; an invalid one (out of
range, wrong type, or missing) is **ignored** — LCS retains the last
known-good value (or the compiled-in default) and emits an audit event
naming the parameter, the rejected value, and the value still in use. The
write to the registry still succeeds — the storage source does not enforce
kernel semantics — so the registry shows what was **written** while the
audit log shows what LCS is actually **using**. The two can legitimately
disagree.

**When a change applies.** Every tunable here takes effect for **new**
operations once the configuration re-read completes; operations already in
flight keep using the value that was active when they started. That is
what `applies: live` means for these parameters — there is nothing to
restart. This timing rule is shared by all the values below and is not
repeated in each.

Security is on this key: all values inherit the Machine hive root Security
Descriptor (SYSTEM and Administrators: KEY_ALL_ACCESS; Authenticated
Users: KEY_READ), so unprivileged processes cannot modify LCS limits.
Group Policy at a higher-precedence layer defends against a compromised
local administrator — SeTcbPrivilege is required to create a layer at
precedence > 0.

The `Machine\System\Registry\Layers` subkey under this path is **not** a
tunable: it holds layer metadata (precedence, enabled state, per-layer
Security Descriptors) that LCS manages and watches directly. Do not
hand-edit it as though it were configuration.

--- machine\system\registry requesttimeoutms
canonical: Machine\System\Registry RequestTimeoutMs
type: REG_DWORD
default: 30000
valid: 1000–600000 ms (1 s–10 min)
applies: live

Per-request timeout for a source round-trip, in milliseconds.

Measured from the first attempt to reserve an in-flight slot through
receipt of the response. When it is exceeded the calling thread receives
ETIMEDOUT; the source stays alive. This is also the deadline a caller
waits under when all RSI slots are busy (see MaxConcurrentRSIRequests).

--- machine\system\registry transactiontimeoutms
canonical: Machine\System\Registry TransactionTimeoutMs
type: REG_DWORD
default: 30000
valid: 1000–600000 ms (1 s–10 min)
applies: live

Maximum lifetime of an open transaction, in milliseconds.

Measured from reg_begin_transaction to auto-abort. It stops a stalled or
malicious process from holding the source's write lock indefinitely. On
expiry the transaction is auto-aborted and the caller's next operation on
it returns ETIMEDOUT.

--- machine\system\registry maxkeydepth
canonical: Machine\System\Registry MaxKeyDepth
type: REG_DWORD
default: 512
valid: 32–4096 levels
applies: live

Maximum nesting depth of the key hierarchy.

Bounds the ancestor-chain memory held per open key fd and the length of a
path-resolution walk. reg_open_key / reg_create_key on a path deeper than
this fail with EINVAL.

--- machine\system\registry maxpathcomponentlength
canonical: Machine\System\Registry MaxPathComponentLength
type: REG_DWORD
default: 255
valid: 64–1024 UTF-8 bytes
applies: live

Maximum length of a single key-name component, value name, or layer name,
in UTF-8 bytes.

A component longer than this is rejected with ENAMETOOLONG.

--- machine\system\registry maxtotalpathlength
canonical: Machine\System\Registry MaxTotalPathLength
type: REG_DWORD
default: 16383
valid: 1024–65535 UTF-8 bytes
applies: live

Maximum total length of a full registry path, in UTF-8 bytes.

Counts every component and separator in the path. The default matches or
exceeds the comparable Windows limit. An over-length path is rejected with
ENAMETOOLONG.

--- machine\system\registry symlinkdepthlimit
canonical: Machine\System\Registry SymlinkDepthLimit
type: REG_DWORD
default: 16
valid: 1–64 hops
applies: live

Maximum registry-symlink resolution depth during path resolution.

Each REG_LINK traversed counts as one hop; exceeding the limit fails with
ELOOP. Guards against symlink cycles and pathologically long link chains.

--- machine\system\registry maxvaluesize
canonical: Machine\System\Registry MaxValueSize
type: REG_DWORD
default: 1048576
valid: 4096–67108864 bytes (4 KB–64 MB)
applies: live

Maximum data payload size for a single value, in bytes.

Default 1 MB, ceiling 64 MB. A write whose payload exceeds the active
limit is rejected with ENOSPC.

--- machine\system\registry maxlayerspervalue
canonical: Machine\System\Registry MaxLayersPerValue
type: REG_DWORD
default: 128
valid: 1–1024 layers
applies: live

Maximum number of layers that may write to the same (key, value) pair.

Bounds the per-value layer-resolution cost. Once this many layers carry a
write for one value, a further layered write to it is rejected with
ENOSPC.

--- machine\system\registry maxtotallayers
canonical: Machine\System\Registry MaxTotalLayers
type: REG_DWORD
default: 1024
valid: 16–65536 layers
applies: live

Maximum number of distinct layers in the in-memory layer table.

Bounds kernel memory consumed by layer creation across the whole system.
Creating a layer beyond this limit fails with ENOSPC.

--- machine\system\registry maxboundtransactionspersource
canonical: Machine\System\Registry MaxBoundTransactionsPerSource
type: REG_DWORD
default: 16
valid: 1–256 transactions
applies: live

Maximum number of concurrently bound (write-lock-holding) transactions per
source.

Prevents write-lock starvation through transaction chaining. The operation
that would bind one transaction too many fails with EBUSY.

--- machine\system\registry maxreadonlytransactionspersource
canonical: Machine\System\Registry MaxReadOnlyTransactionsPerSource
type: REG_DWORD
default: 16
valid: 1–256 transactions
applies: live

Maximum number of concurrently active read-only snapshot transactions per
source.

Used by REG_IOC_BACKUP. It caps backup-snapshot concurrency without
treating a backup as a write-lock-holding transaction. Exceeding it fails
the REG_IOC_BACKUP with EBUSY.

--- machine\system\registry maxregisteredsources
canonical: Machine\System\Registry MaxRegisteredSources
type: REG_DWORD
default: 32
valid: 1–256 sources
applies: live

Maximum number of concurrently registered sources.

Bounds the routing-table size and per-source kernel state. A
REG_SRC_REGISTER beyond this limit fails with ENOSPC.

--- machine\system\registry maxhivespersource
canonical: Machine\System\Registry MaxHivesPerSource
type: REG_DWORD
default: 64
valid: 1–1024 hives
applies: live

Maximum number of hives a single source may register.

A REG_SRC_REGISTER that would exceed this for one source fails with
ENOSPC.

--- machine\system\registry maxconcurrentrsirequests
canonical: Machine\System\Registry MaxConcurrentRSIRequests
type: REG_DWORD
default: 256
valid: 8–4096 requests
applies: live

Maximum number of in-flight requests dispatched to one source and awaiting
a response.

Provides back-pressure when a source is slow. When the limit is reached,
new operations wait for a slot under the same deadline as
RequestTimeoutMs, returning ETIMEDOUT if no slot frees up in time.

--- machine\system\registry notificationqueuesize
canonical: Machine\System\Registry NotificationQueueSize
type: REG_DWORD
default: 256
valid: 16–65536 events
applies: live

Maximum events queued per armed watch before overflow.

When a watcher's queue is full, the oldest events are dropped and a single
OVERFLOW marker is delivered in their place. This bounds userspace
fd-based watches; LCS's own internal configuration watches are processed
synchronously and are not subject to it.

--- machine\system\registry maxsubtreewatchdepth
canonical: Machine\System\Registry MaxSubtreeWatchDepth
type: REG_DWORD
default: 0
valid: 0–4096 levels (0 = unlimited)
applies: live

Maximum depth from a watched key to a descendant for subtree-watch event
delivery.

A value of 0 means unlimited — events for all descendants are delivered.
With a positive limit, changes deeper than that are silently not delivered
to the watcher, trading completeness for less event noise and lower
dispatch cost on deep subtree watches.

--- machine\system\registry maxtransactionwatcheventburst
canonical: Machine\System\Registry MaxTransactionWatchEventBurst
type: REG_DWORD
default: 4096
valid: 256–65536 events
applies: live

Maximum watch events generated for one watcher by a single transaction
commit.

When a commit would deliver more than this many events to one watcher, LCS
stops generating individual events and inserts a single OVERFLOW instead —
stopping a large transaction from atomically filling a watcher's queue.

--- machine\system\registry maxscopeguidspertoken
canonical: Machine\System\Registry MaxScopeGUIDsPerToken
type: REG_DWORD
default: 8
valid: 1–256 GUIDs
applies: live

Maximum number of private-hive scope GUIDs a thread's credentials may
carry.

Bounds the per-syscall routing iteration cost. The limit is enforced when
credentials are attached, which is a KACS concern rather than a registry
operation.

--- machine\system\registry maxprivatelayerspertoken
canonical: Machine\System\Registry MaxPrivateLayersPerToken
type: REG_DWORD
default: 16
valid: 1–256 layers
applies: live

Maximum number of private-layer names a thread's credentials may carry.

Bounds the per-resolution is_active() iteration cost. The limit is
enforced when credentials are attached, which is a KACS concern rather
than a registry operation.
